##Guangdong 14% of discharged patients re-test positive, experts: May still be infectious

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

Being discharged from the hospital is not a full recovery

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 27, Mr. Wang, a resident of Xuzhou who had been out of the hospital for 19 days, tested positive for nucleic acid and was readmitted to a designated hospital for medical observation.

Mr. Wang was released from the hospital on Feb. 9 and returned home after 14 days in isolation. Three days after he returned home, Mr. Wang saw on the news that some of the recovered patients had tested positive again, and asked for nucleic acid testing again. The results were positive. According to Wang's family, he checked his throat swab and stool before leaving the hospital. CT SCAN of his lungs showed absorption of inflammation and "a cough without fever for a long time. ".

On the day Mr. Wang returned home, his neighbors in the community held a welcome home ceremony for him. Today, eight close contacts have also been transferred to the central isolation point for observation, and 65 people in the unit building where Mr. Wang lives have been isolated at home.

Since February, Chengdu, Wuhan and Guangdong have also been discharged from the hospital patients retest positive cases. Among them, 14% of discharged patients in Guangdong province had positive retest.

At a press conference held by the Joint Prevention and Control Mechanism of the State Council on February 28, Guo Yanhong, an inspector of the Medical Administration and Hospital Authority of the National Health Commission, introduced the situation of Nucleic acid-positive patients who had been discharged from hospitals in various places. Surveillance found that this part of the patients did not happen to infect others, and another part of the patients again when the nucleic acid test, the results turned negative.

Discharge doesn't mean a full recovery

In the sixth edition of the new diagnosis and treatment plan for pneumonia issued by the National Health Commission, patients discharged from hospital and isolated from contact should satisfy four symptoms, namely, the body temperature returns to normal for more than 3 days, and respiratory symptoms improve significantly, cT showed marked improvement in acute exudative lesions and two negative breath nucleic acid tests. The sampling time of two nucleic acid tests is at least one day apart.

However, discharge from the hospital does not mean a full recovery. Tong Dejun, director of the Hospital Infection Control Center at Central South University, told China Newsweek, "The symptoms described in the discharge criteria are markedly improved, and marked improvement in exudative lesions is not the same as complete absence of symptoms. Some patients also have mild respiratory symptoms such as cough. exudative lesions may still exist, but they can be discharged with marked improvement, and most patients will recover on their own after discharge. "

Song Tie, Deputy Director of the Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said at a People's Government of Guangdong Province news conference on Feb. 25 that, "Lung Inflammation in some discharged patients can not be said to be clinically significant recovery in the absorption process, this situation may be intermittent detoxification phenomenon. "

According to the new scheme, patients should continue to undergo 14-day self-health monitoring after discharge, wear a mask, live in a well-ventilated single room, reduce close contact with family members, and eat and drink separately, do good hand hygiene and avoid going out. In addition, discharge notes also provide that patients discharged from the second week and the fourth week should go to the hospital for follow-up.

It is understood that Hubei, Guangdong, Jiangsu and other places are implementing more stringent measures to collect discharged patients into medical isolation points for observation, carry out unified health monitoring and health guidance, and reduce the risk of re-infection among discharged patients.

However, there are still discharged patients after the isolation period, the retest results were positive. Song Tie stressed that if patients in the hospital after a positive retest, "must be the source of infection, in terms of prevention and control according to the source of infection to manage. "

For this part of the patients, to re-designated hospital isolation observation, until the two consecutive negative nucleic acid test, can be discharged again.

"As far as the prevention and control of infectious diseases is concerned, as long as the patient is found to have the virus, he can become a source of infection, so even though he has no symptoms, he has been asked to be quarantined out of concern for the prevention and control of infectious diseases, " Tong, who is in charge of infection prevention and control at the second Xiangya Hospital, explained to China Newsweek. "for patients who test positive, if symptoms do not worsen, re-hospitalization may not require special treatment, pay attention to the observation of the body to monitor the production of new crown antibodies, rely on the body's own immunity can eliminate the virus. "

Regarding the phenomenon of new crown patients returning to Yang after discharge from hospitals in various places, Guo Yanhong, commissioner of the Medical Administration and Hospital Authority of the National Health Commission, said that in addition to strengthening the management of discharged patients, it is also necessary to further deepen the understanding of the pathogenic mechanism, Disease Panorama and disease course characteristics of the novel coronavirus. It is understood that Zhong Nanshan's team is doing further research on the phenomenon.

The infectivity of patients with Fu Yang Disease

According to Song, laboratory observations have shown that young, mild patients develop antibodies after two weeks, and if they test positive again, the risk of transmission is low. Older people produce antibodies for longer periods of time and may become a source of infection during continuous detoxification.

Zhang Linqi, director of the Center for Global Health and Infectious Diseases at Tsinghua University and the Center for Comprehensive AIDS research at Tsinghua University, told China Newsweek that when the immune system overcomes the new coronavirus, the virus will be completely eliminated from the body. "unlike chronic infections, such as hepatitis B, HIV is a long-term infection. From what we know now, if the recovered person is cured, the virus will be eliminated within a period of time. "

In patients with NCP, there is a continuous process from infection to onset and recovery, followed by a gradual increase and decrease of the virus in the body. There is a stage in the process where the body feels it has recovered well, but is itself still toxic. "But there is no scientific conclusion as to how much and for how long. "

At this stage, it is possible to discharge a patient with the virus because of a false negative nucleic acid result due to sampling techniques and the accuracy of the test reagents.

Professor Zhang Linqi believes that we should not worry too much about the phenomenon of recovery of Yang in discharged patients, the existing discharge standards and discharge isolation measures have reduced the risk of passing pseudoyin to others.

In addition, the conditions under which a person is infected with a virus depend on the load of the pathogen and the infectivity and virulence of the virus. When a person is exposed to a small amount of the virus, the body may simply wipe it out without getting sick, as many close contacts of a confirmed patient do not.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Multiple factors of false negative

At present, the diagnosis and discharge decision of patients with NCP depend on the result of nucleic acid test to a certain extent. To improve the accuracy of the test results can effectively avoid false negative cases.

However, the accuracy of nucleic acid detection is limited due to the accuracy of nucleic acid reagents, sampling techniques and limited access to samples.

According to the director of the German boy, the infection caused by the new coronavirus mainly occurs in the lower respiratory tract, leaving down the respiratory secretions can increase the positive detection rate. Therefore, the deeper the respiratory tract collection of specimens, the higher the positive rate. The positive detection rate of several samples ranged from high to low, including alveolar lavage fluid, sputum swab, and stool swab.

Bronchoalveolar lavage fluid (Balf) is usually collected during alveolar lavage in critically ill patients. Sputum and usually cough up oral secretions of PHLEGM DIFFERENT, it refers to the morning after gargling cough out of deep sputum respiratory tract. Because the symptoms of mild cases of dry cough, can not be obtained alveolar lavage fluid or sputum, many patients can only be used on the respiratory specimens, that is, throat swabs to do testing.

It should be noted that the timing of throat swab sampling, the specific location of sampling and throat Swab smear will affect the accuracy of nucleic acid testing. "For close contacts, for example, if he is infected, the virus may be excreted two days before the onset of symptoms, and as the symptoms get worse, the amount of detoxication gradually increases, and the positive detection rate is higher, " said the Scout's director.

In addition, the specimen can not be sent in time, or transportation process is not well preserved, there will be degradation, which is also a factor leading to false negative. In order to improve the timeliness and accuracy of nucleic acid testing, nucleic acid sample testing has been from the early must be determined by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention to the authorized designated medical testing institutions can be independently issued a positive report.

It is worth noting that the serum antibody test, as a complement to nucleic acid testing, will assist doctors in judging patients'infections. If the serum antibody test shows IGM antibody, the patient is in the early stage of infection; IgG antibody is produced later and lasts longer in the human body.

It is understood that China has more than manufacturers of serum antibody detection kit. The second Xiangya hospital has used the serum antibody test as a supplementary diagnostic basis for cases with doubtful nucleic acid test results.
